Class IntoChest

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.bukkit.plugin.PluginBase
      • org.bukkit.plugin.java.JavaPlugin
        • atpx.minecraft.IntoChest
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    atpx.minecraft.DataValues, java.lang.Runnable, org.bukkit.command.CommandExecutor, org.bukkit.command.TabCompleter, org.bukkit.command.TabExecutor, org.bukkit.event.Listener, org.bukkit.plugin.Plugin

    public class IntoChest
extends org.bukkit.plugin.java.JavaPlugin
implements java.lang.Runnable, atpx.minecraft.DataValues, org.bukkit.event.Listener
    IntoChest is the driver for the IntoChest Minecraft plugin.

    Runs continuously while plugin is enabled, checking for any items that lie on top of a crafting table. When found, it will process the item and attempt to find a chest to place the item into. The chest may be next to the crafting table or be connected through redstone wire and signs.

    Signs can be used to filter items from its redstone path. You can filter an item by typing one of these identifiers on the sign:

    1. The full name of the item
    2. The short name of the item
    3. The group name that includes the item
    4. The decimal item ID of the item
    5. The decimal item ID and item data value of the item, delimited by a pipe

    Example: I want to only allow birch wood to pass through a sign. I can type one these onto the sign to get the desired results:

    1. birch wood
    2. bwood
    3. wood
    4. 17
    5. 17|2

    For how to derive the short name of an item, refer to SHORTITEMNAMES.

    You may specify multiple items on a sign - you must separate items with the comma (,) delimiter.

    Author:
    Jeff Lee

      • findNextEmptyComponentHelper

        private org.bukkit.block.Block findNextEmptyComponentHelper(org.bukkit.block.Block curBlock,
                                                            org.bukkit.block.Block aboveBlock,
                                                            org.bukkit.Material aboveBlockType,
                                                            org.bukkit.block.BlockFace direction,
                                                            org.bukkit.inventory.ItemStack itemStack,
                                                            java.lang.String itemIdStr)
        From the current block, check in a specific direction if the block in that direction is a component for IntoChest to continue the traversal path.

        Is a helper function for findNextEmptyComponent(Block, ItemStack, String) which is called recursively in order to traverse the possible IntoChest paths.

        Parameters:
        curBlock - the current block we are pointing at
        aboveBlock - the block above the current block
        aboveBlockType - the type of the aboveBlock
        direction - the direction to check for a block that is a component
        itemStack - object for item stack sitting on crafting table
        itemIdStr - identifier string of the item stack
        Returns:
        block that is found to be an end component

      • isAllowed

        protected boolean isAllowed(org.bukkit.block.Sign sign,
                            int typeId,
                            int dataVal,
                            java.lang.String itemIdStr)
        Check if the item that's sitting on the crafting table is allowed to pass through a sign filter.

        The sign can include text that matches an item through its item identifier (decimal ID and data value delimited by a pipe), decimal ID, exact name, short name, or group name.

        Parameters:
        sign - the sign that is checked against the item sitting on crafting table
        typeId - item decimal ID (Example: 15)
        dataVal - item data value (Example: 2)
        itemIdStr - item identifier (Example: 15|2)
        Returns:
        true if the item is allowed to pass through the sign filter.
